Defendant Jeremy Sean Hobbs in court with attorney Douglas J. Rebholz.  Defendant Jeremy Sean Hobbs in custody.  Michael Thurston on behalf of Cynthia Davis appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Deputy court clerk ccp.
Case set for sentencing hearing. Parties are prepared to proceed. Victim Impact Statement received and filed. Court finds the State has complied with victim rights legislation. Statements made as to sentencing.

As to COUNT 1-
Court ordered defendant to serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Correction concurrent to COUNT 2; credit for 17 days time served.

As to COUNT 2-
Court ordered defendant to serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Correction concurrent to COUNT 1; credit for 17 days time served.

Court STAYED the sentence on COUNTS 1 & 2 and placed defendant on probation for 18 MONTHS with the following conditions:

1) Court ordered 90 days of condition time in the House of Correction IMPOSED AND STAYED, to be used at the discretion of the agent;
2) Pay all costs, fees and surcharges. Failure to pay during period of probation will result in a civil judgment;
3) Pay DNA surcharge on COUNT 1 & COUNT 2 and provide a DNA sample;
4) Participate in an anger management program;
5) No contact with the victim or her school, place of employment or residence;
6) Defendant is prohibited from maintaining any social media accounts;
7) Any electronic devices must be turned over to agent for inspection upon demand;
8) Maintain absolute sobriety;
9) Random urine screens;
10) Provide prescription to the agent before filling the prescription;
11) Court set restitution at ZERO;

Court will allow the defendant's probation to be transferred to the State of North Carolina if accepted. 

If revoked, defendant may have work release if employed at the time of revocation. Defendant may participate in comployment/vocational programming at the House of Correction if revoked. 

Appellate rights notice given to the defendant. 
Filed;
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief;
Pretrial Incarceration Credit.
